    "body": "### Description\n\n## Summary\n\nThe ESLint LSP configuration in lspconfig incorrectly calls `on_dir` unconditionally, causing \"Unable to load ESLint library.\" errors in JavaScript projects that don't use ESLint.\n\n## Expected Behavior\n\nPer neovim documentation, `on_dir` should only be called conditionally to start the LSP when a configuration file has been found.\n\n> Example: To dynamically decide whether LSP is activated, define a [lsp-root_dir()](https://neovim.io/doc/user/lsp.html#lsp-root_dir()) function which calls on_dir() only when you want that config to activate:\n> ```lua\n> vim.lsp.config('lua_ls', {\n>  root_dir = function(bufnr, on_dir)\n>     if not vim.fn.bufname(bufnr):match('%.txt$') then\n>       on_dir(vim.fn.getcwd())\n>     end\n>   end\n> })\n> ```\n\n## Current Behavior\n\nThe ESLint configuration in lspconfig calls `on_dir` regardless of whether any configuration files are found:\n\n```lua\nroot_files = util.insert_package_json(root_files, \"eslintConfig\", fname)\non_dir(vim.fs.dirname(vim.fs.find(root_files, { path = fname, upward = true })[1]))\n```\n\nThis results in:\n- The ESLint LSP server starting in JavaScript projects even when no ESLint configuration exists\n- \"Unable to load ESLint library.\" errors appearing when editing JavaScript files in projects that don't use ESLint\n\n## Proposed Solution\n\nThe `on_dir` call should be wrapped in a conditional check to ensure configuration files exist before starting the LSP server.",
